Good question. You are asking about what can be written inside method parameters (()) and whether modifiers like static, private, public are allowed there.

Short answer:

Inside method parameters, you cannot use access modifiers or static.

Valid:

class Demo {

    void show(int a) {
        System.out.println(a);
    }

    void test(String name, int age) {
        System.out.println(name);
    }
}

Here parameters are only:

datatype
variable name
❌ Not allowed:
void show(public int a) {

}

Error.

void show(private int a) {

}

Error.

void show(static int a) {

}

Error.

Because public, private, static are method/class modifiers, not parameter modifiers.

What can be used in parameters?
1. Normal data types
void print(int a)
void print(double b)
void print(String s)
2. Object types
class Student {}

void display(Student s) {

}
3. Arrays
void show(int[] arr) {

}
4. varargs
void sum(int... numbers) {

}

Means internally an array.

5. final (only modifier allowed)
void show(final int a) {

}

Valid.

Why?

final means you cannot reassign that parameter:

void show(final int a){

    a = 20; // ❌ error
}

But you can use it:

void show(final int a){

    System.out.println(a); // ✅
}
One more important point for overloading:

These are considered different:

void show(int a)
void show(String a)

But these are NOT:

void show(int a)
void show(final int a)

Because final does not change the signature.

So remember:

Method parameter = only type + name (+ final allowed)

No:

public ❌
private ❌
protected ❌
static ❌
abstract ❌
synchronized ❌

Those belong to methods/classes, not parameters.